WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Hi, everyone. I am Casey Aguilar-Gervase.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:06.000
And I'm Maya Gans.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.000
And this is the design of Everyday Shiny Apps.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Pop quiz. You approach this door. Are you going to push or pull it?

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:20.000
That moment of hesitation and, frankly, feeling stupid?

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
We're here to tell you today, this is not your fault.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:27.000
This is the fault of the door.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:31.000
In Don Norman's seminal work, The Design of Everyday Things,

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:38.000
he talks about how door handles, specifically, should be designed either to push or pull.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Not both.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:45.000
In this talk, we'll be pulling imagery from Camprani's Uncomfortable series.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:54.000
We love this imagery because it so beautifully evokes the frustration of bad design.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:59.000
We noticed this morning that Jonathan's talk also used this imagery.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.000
His jumpsuit got lost in the mail, I guess.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
But this talk is not about watering cans or doors.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.000
It's about shiny applications.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:16.000
And you may have come to this talk thinking that design is about making aesthetic or pretty things.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.000
But we're here to tell you that no.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Design is about utility and making users feel like they can use an app and trust it.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.000
So if you couldn't tell by our outfits, Maya and I are pretty used to pair programming.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
We work together as Shiny developers in consulting.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:40.000
And our job is to connect function with feel so client applications can move from it runs to it's usable and clear.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:43.000
This talk is going to be intentionally practical.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:51.000
It's what our day-to-day kind of looks like when we're turning proof of concept applications into something not only functional but genuinely enjoyable.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.000
So in this talk, we're going to go through four lenses.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Layout, making it scannable and predictable.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.000
Color, aiming attention without extra words.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:03.000
Typography, setting a clear hierarchy that holds up in dense data.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:08.000
And components, the answer to what's happening, what changed, what do I do next?

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:15.000
So these four lenses are how we take a proof of concept and turn it into something production-ready that's on brand.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
For today's examples, we're going to use a fake client brand kit.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:20.000
So this is what our client gave us.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
Five main colors and a single typeface to use.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:24.000
That's it.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
As we walk through layout, color, type and components, you'll see us apply the basics.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Nothing fancy to drive consistent choices.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.000
So here's where things get fun.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:38.000
In the next slide, we're going to walk through the original app the way we first experienced it.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:39.000
So great.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.000
I see some data when I open the app, but I'm unsure.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Can I come back to this when I press this close button?

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:48.000
The color palette hits us all at once.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:49.000
It's bright.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:50.000
It's loud.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:51.000
Kind of like us.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.000
Instead of guiding the eye, it's pulling my attention in different directions.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.000
The navigation feels confusing.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Sections don't flow as expected.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:00.000
And it's not clear what I should do next.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:02.000
So let's try to add a project.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:04.000
I'm going to click this create new button.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.000
But now I'm a little stuck.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:08.000
I'll try updating the project name.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.000
But nothing seems to happen when I click this.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Maybe let's try deleting.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.000
The same thing is going to happen with the delete button.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Unsure if they're broken.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:20.000
So I'm going to navigate over to the nested nav.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.000
It's probably important.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:23.000
Okay.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.000
So this is where I can download my reports.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:26.000
Click on the button.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.000
I think this is broken, too.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.000
And also, where can I find my file?

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:32.000
Okay.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
So between the overwhelming visuals and unclear layout,

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:40.000
it's easy to see how quickly a new user could get lost or frustrated.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.000
So when designing an application or redesigning,

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
the first thing that Casey and I do together is look at the layout.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.000
This is the map for the user to know when and where to go

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:55.000
and what actions are most important.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.000
In this visual, we have a great door and a set of stairs.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:06.000
But without connecting those components, this is pretty useless.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.000
So the client, our client,

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:11.000
told us that they wanted to keep the content the same

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
but make the app cleaner and more user-friendly.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:17.000
So we do have a sidebar here that's used as that main navigation.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.000
And across the overview page, there's some odd spacing.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.000
We kind of see a grid.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:24.000
But it's confusing where my eyes should go

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:26.000
because of the inconsistent spacing.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:29.000
So to make sure the content takes up

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:32.000
as much of the real estate of the page as possible,

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.000
we'll use a horizontal navigation.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:38.000
We've stripped away color here to focus just on layout and an even grid.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:41.000
Small details like consistent layout and spacing

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
help things feel like I can breathe as our eyes

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
or as my eyes are going to absorb the page.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.000
On the overview page, that data table sat at the bottom of the card,

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:52.000
and it kind of spilled over.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
Because it was at the bottom, we had to scroll to see all of the data.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
We've added a nested nav inside of the overview page

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.000
so users can flip between the exploration and data review

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
a little bit more seamlessly.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.000
When I added projects, it showed up in this sidebar,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
but nothing really signaled me to click over there.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Once I did, I saw the current selections and download options,

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:17.000
but I lost that project table.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:20.000
So now current selections and the project table

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.000
live together on this left-hand side.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.000
And when I go to add a project,

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.000
that download card is going to appear with a nested nav.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
So everything's going to stay on one page,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.000
the flow is clearer, consistent with that top navigation,

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.000
and the layout still feels breathable as I'm moving through it.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
So what's the TLDR?

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
The takeaway of takeaways today is obey the grid.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:49.000
Evolutionarily, we crave that structure.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.000
Your users, there will be a sense of calm

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:56.000
if you stick to your columns and rows.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
Secondly, shout out to talk before this one,

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:03.000
there's been many studies on saccade, or eye movement,

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:07.000
and in Western cultures, we read in a Z from left to right.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:10.000
You'll note that we took the navigation

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:13.000
from being vertical to horizontal

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:17.000
and also put it in that hot spot of the top left corner

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:19.000
because that is how you're going to navigate

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.000
throughout the application.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.000
Lastly, we appreciate that screen real estate is expensive

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.000
and you want to cram a bunch in there.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:28.000
Don't.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:31.000
That is incredibly overwhelming to your user.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.000
You should let different elements breathe.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.000
It gives a sense of pause

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.000
and you can flow through different elements logically.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:42.000
Okay, so now that we have our layout,

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.000
we get to the fun part, color.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:47.000
And in this talk, we've constrained it

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:49.000
to a defined color palette.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:53.000
Picking colors, that is a talk in and of itself.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:57.000
But today, we're going to talk about how to use color.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:01.000
So in this example, this bar on the left-hand side,

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:03.000
that is the exact same shade of gray.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:06.000
Note how that changes just by what it's placed next to.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:10.000
Similarly, the cells A and B, also the same.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:11.000
We'll give you these slides,

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.000
you don't have to take my word for it.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:20.000
This demonstrates how color should not only,

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:21.000
you have to make good choices,

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.000
but you should use those in an effective manner.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:27.000
And when you use color effectively,

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:29.000
it almost just hides in the background

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:32.000
and becomes transparent.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.000
So in the original app, the color palette is here,

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:38.000
but it feels a little bit chaotic and distracting.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
We also see the default shiny blue

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:43.000
that's showing up in the slider

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:47.000
and a pink in that checkbox that doesn't quite fit.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:49.000
Taking advantage of the new layout,

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.000
we're adding color more intentionally.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.000
There's a pop of gradient in the nav

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
and that same gradient shows up

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:57.000
as an accent in the value cards.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
It's not distracting, but it adds unity

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.000
and ties the color palette together.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.000
Color now works as a guide.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
Active tabs in the nav have a pink underline

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
and when I hover, the color shifts

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
to our watermelon secondary color.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
On the report page, buttons didn't really have

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.000
a lot of styling, they're just pretty much shiny default.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:22.000
Buttons are now gonna mirror the nav styling,

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:26.000
pink by default, shifting to watermelon on hover.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
So these color accents create consistency

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
across interactions.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
In tables, the hover state defaulted

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
to the standard data table blue.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:37.000
The hover state now uses our brand's blue,

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:40.000
reinforcing the palette and creating subtle unity.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
These small color decisions don't just decorate,

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
they build consistency, trust,

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:47.000
and a more polished user experience.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:49.000
How do I do this myself?

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:52.000
One, start designing in black and white,

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.000
slowly integrating and adding more color.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Two, stick to a defined palette.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.000
You get five colors and we're being generous.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:05.000
Note that two of those colors were black and white.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.000
In Flex Dashboard, I'm pretty sure the background

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.000
is a default of a lightish blue.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:13.000
None of that if it's not in the palette.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:16.000
And lastly, use color to highlight.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.000
Clearly we like flair here,

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:21.000
but I'm not gonna make a navigation bar hot pink

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:22.000
just because I want to.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
That's where Casey edits me and says,

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:27.000
we use color to highlight and show interactivity

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:29.000
within the application.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
Once we've tackled color, we move on to typography.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
Font nerds collect fonts like baseball cards.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
Font sets the tone and tenor of your application.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.000
You can have a fun, silly font or very serious,

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
and you also can use typography to create hierarchy.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
The importance of font is shown in this photo.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:54.000
It can be used to convey something delicious

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
or something entirely different.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.000
So in the original app,

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.000
there isn't a super clear hierarchy

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:03.000
established across the elements.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:04.000
Font weight is here,

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.000
but it doesn't feel super intentional.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
We're also missing the brand's typeface.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
So to start, the new app uses the brand typeface throughout

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.000
and value boxes uppercase and size,

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:16.000
improve readability,

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
and make distinctions clearer at a glance.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:22.000
All user input labels are uppercase and bold,

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.000
reinforcing consistency.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
Font weight is gonna be used purposely,

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:30.000
like showing emphasis when hovering in the nav.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:32.000
On the report page,

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:35.000
elements blended together without clear separation.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.000
Font weight now highlights headers

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.000
while buttons use case to place emphasis.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
So this consistent use of weight, case,

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
and readability patterns across inputs

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.000
is gonna build subconscious trust for the user.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
Rule number one, match your style to the brand.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:57.000
You're given a typeface, use it.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
If that typeface is super funky,

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
do not use that for smaller fonts.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
Pair it, and just like we gave you five colors,

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:08.000
you get two fonts tops, even that, generous.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:15.000
Casey showed us how you can also increase the font weight,

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
and in those value boxes,

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:21.000
we had the titles were uppercase

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:24.000
and the bylines were lowercase.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Those were the same font.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:30.000
Those two are tools you have in your arsenal.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:33.000
You don't just have to increment the font size.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.000
However, if you are going to, be consistent.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:39.000
We like incrementing by four or six pixels.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:43.000
Do not just willy-nilly big, medium, small.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
Our last section is components.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:53.000
These are the pull and push doors of your application,

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:54.000
and what's gonna make it or break it

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.000
for users to keep on using your app

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:59.000
or just go on to the next one.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.000
This is made evident in this image

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:05.000
where there's a blow-up door handle.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.000
If you try to turn that and it squishes in your hand,

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
you're not going anywhere.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
To start, in the original app,

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
the modal was really the only way

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
for the user to access details,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
which is gonna force me to memorize information

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
from one screen to the next.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.000
We added a persistent tool tip at the top,

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
so instead of relying on memory,

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:28.000
users now have a reference point

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:31.000
that they can turn to at any time.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.000
On the report page after adding a project,

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.000
there was no clear direction forward,

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:36.000
no labels, no guidance,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
just buttons kind of staring back at me.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:42.000
It was a moment where users might easily hesitate or give up.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.000
Section-level tool tips now give descriptions

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.000
of what each area is for and how to use it.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
Buttons only appear when needed,

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:54.000
guiding users through the flow without overwhelming them.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
For permanent actions, like deleting,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
we added a confirmation step as a safeguard,

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:02.000
which you can see here with this delete modal

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:05.000
that's popping up.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
The original download button was kind of a mystery.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.000
I just click it, hope for the best,

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
kind of like sending a text into the void.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
The download button now comes with a progress bar

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
and error message, so users know the app heard them

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.000
and what might be happening next.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:23.000
As a bonus, custom HTML widgets like this one,

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:25.000
which uses hands-on table framework,

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:28.000
can create familiar Excel-like tables

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.000
that still feel intuitive to use

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
while maintaining our brand identity.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:36.000
So together, these changes really reduce confusion,

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:39.000
build confidence, and turn something overwhelming

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:44.000
into something guided and responsive.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
Visual feedback is key.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
For every action a user can take,

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
there must be some reaction in the application

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:55.000
that showed them that they took this action.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:56.000
Error prevention.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
As a good rule of thumb,

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:01.000
any action that your user can do in the application,

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:03.000
they should be able to undo.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:06.000
If you have a situation in which they can't undo it,

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
like Casey demonstrated, you should pop up a modal,

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
you sure about that?

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
And lastly, progressive disclosure,

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:16.000
which was a great point in the previous talk,

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
that the Shiny apps that we've asked to redesign

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
the Shiny folks here, they love a wall of text.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
And let's be real, no one's reading that.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:29.000
Put your text in chunks in information tool tips

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
so that when I go to that plot,

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
I interact and hover over it,

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:34.000
ooh, what does this do?

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
And similarly, put that by your filters,

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:39.000
break it up into ways people will actually read.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:43.000
So at this point, I hope not,

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.000
but you might still be wondering,

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.000
why should I care about all this design stuff?

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
The truth is, design is the difference

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:54.000
between an app people tolerate and a people actually use.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
If the layout is confusing,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
users are gonna get frustrated and drop off.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:02.000
If the tone feels off, they just don't trust it.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:05.000
And if the app doesn't give clear feedback,

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:08.000
they might make mistakes or give up entirely.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.000
So that's not just about looks,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
that's about adoption, efficiency,

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:15.000
and whether your work even lands with its audience.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:19.000
We thought this quote was the perfect way to end our talk

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:23.000
because it covers how layout, color, type, and components

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:26.000
are all integral to good design,

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
and good design is not a luxury,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
it's a necessity.

